@node BootLog "BootLog"
@prev BootLog

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}BootLog@{ub} - record time and reason of reboot.

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}BootLog@{ub} @{i}LogFile @{ui}[@{b}QUIET@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}BootLog@{ub} "LOGFILE,QUIET/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}BootLog@{ub} prints and stores in selected file the reason, date and time
  of last computer reboot. It recognizes three possible causes of reboot:
  · operating system failure (@{i}Alert@{ui});
  · turning on computer (@{i}Power@{ui});
  · manual or programmable reset (@{i}Reset@{ui}).
     On each run @{b}BootLog@{ub} will append a line to @{i}LogFile@{ui}. This line has the
   following format:
  @{i}Reason @{ui}@{i}Date @{ui}@{i}Time@{ui}.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}LOGFILE@{ub} - name of log file (default is @{i}DEVS:Logs/Boot.log@{ui});
      @{b}QUIET@{ub} - suppresses printing of info to console.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "BootLog NIL:"} @{b}BootLog@{ub} @{i}NIL:@{ui}
        ; Print reason and time of last reboot to screen only
      @{b}BootLog@{ub} QUIET
        ; Store reason and time of last reboot in default log file
        ; (recommended for @{i}Startup-Sequence@{ui})

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      I wrote this program because I didn't want to set up full-blown
  multiuser system, but still know what happens with my computer.
      To distinguish between power-on and reset situations @{b}BootLog@{ub}
  installs a small (34 bytes) MemTag. Virus killers may complain about it.
@endnode

@node ChangeFont "ChangeFont"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}ChangeFont@{ub} - replace @{i}topaz @{ui}font with user supplied one

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}ChangeFont@{ub} @{i}FontName @{ui}[@{i}Sizes@{ui}] [@{b}QUIET@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}ChangeFont@{ub} "NAME/A,SIZE/N/M,QUIET/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}ChangeFont@{ub} replaces ROM @{i}topaz.font @{ui}with user specified font. Only sizes
  specified by user are replaced. The replacement is global: any program
  using @{i}topaz.font @{ui}utilizes the new font immediately.
      The replacement font must have the properties of @{i}topaz.font@{ui}: it has to
  be non-proportional and of proper width. The sizes you specify on command
  line indicate which ROM sizes to replace: you can't replace 8 points height
  font with 12 points one! The default sizes for replacement are 8 and 9.
  Replacement font with given size must exist: it is not possible to use a
  scaled one.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}NAME@{ub} - name of replacement font;
      @{b}SIZE@{ub} - @{i}topaz.font @{ui}sizes to replace (default: 8 and 9);
      @{b}QUIET@{ub} - suppresses informational messages.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "ChangeFont EOBF8 8"} @{b}ChangeFont@{ub} @{i}EOBF8 @{ui}@{i}8@{ui}
        ; Replace @{i}topaz @{ui}@{i}8 @{ui}with font from Eye Of the Beholder
        ; @{i}topaz @{ui}@{i}9 @{ui}is not replaced
@{"Test" system "ChangeFont topazpl.font QUIET"} @{b}ChangeFont@{ub} @{i}topazpl.font @{ui}QUIET
        ; use Polish char set instead of international, don't print any info

@{fg highlight}BUGS@{fg text}
      Once you used this program, there is no turning back: you can't use
  original @{i}topaz @{ui}anymore. Every replacement font remains in memory, so you
  will notice memory loss.

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      I wrote this program because Polish language has 18 special characters,
  that don't exist in international ASCII char set. Changing disk fonts was
  easy, but @{i}topaz @{ui}could not be replaced. And Preferences font settings don't
  mean match to many programs.
      This program is not 100% legal: it manipulates TextFont structures
  directly. But it's not a hack either, as no private/undocumented variables
  are touched.
@endnode

@node ClickStart "ClickStart"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}ClickStart@{ub} - enable or disable some AmigaDOS features

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
@{fg fill}(V37)@{fg text} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} [@{b}CLICK@{ub}|@{b}NOCLICK@{ub}] [@{b}STAR@{ub}|@{b}NOSTAR@{ub}]
                 [@{b}PIPE=@{ub}@{i}PipeChar@{ui}|@{b}NOPIPE@{ub}] [@{b}MULTI=@{ub}@{i}MultiCommandChar@{ui}|@{b}NOMULTI@{ub}]
                 [@{b}RETRY=@{ub}@{i}NumberOfRetries@{ui}] [@{b}QUANTUM=@{ub}@{i}QuantumFrames@{ui}] [@{b}QUIET@{ub}]
@{fg fill}(V39)@{fg text} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} [@{b}CLICK@{ub}|@{b}NOCLICK@{ub}] [@{b}STAR@{ub}|@{b}NOSTAR@{ub}]
                 [@{b}PIPE=@{ub}@{i}PipeChar@{ui}|@{b}NOPIPE@{ub}] [@{b}MULTI=@{ub}@{i}MultiCommandChar@{ui}|@{b}NOMULTI@{ub}]
                 [@{b}BORBLANK@{ub}|@{b}NOBORBLANK@{ub}] [@{b}BORSPRITES@{ub}|@{b}NOBORSPRITES@{ub}]
                 [@{b}RETRY=@{ub}@{i}NumberOfRetries@{ui}] [@{b}ALERT=@{ub}@{i}AlertDisplayTime@{ui}] 
                 [@{b}QUANTUM=@{ub}@{i}QuantumFrames@{ui}] [@{b}QUIET@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
@{fg fill}(V37)@{fg text} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} "CLICK/S,NOCLICK/S,STAR/S,NOSTAR/S,PIPE/K,NOPIPE/S,
                  MULTI/K,NOMULTI/S,RETRY/K/N,QUANTUM/K/N,QUIET/S"
@{fg fill}(V39)@{fg text} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} "CLICK/S,NOCLICK/S,STAR/S,NOSTAR/S,
                  PIPE/K,NOPIPE/S,MULTI/K,NOMULTI/S,
                  BORBLANK/S,NOBORBLANK/S,BORSPRITES/S,NOBORSPRITES/S,
                  ALERT/K/N,RETRY/K/N,QUANTUM/K/N,QUIET/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}ClickStart@{ub} allows you to customize AmigaDOS to suit your preferences.
  Possible changes include:
  · disk drives clicking;
  · star wildcard;
  · Unix style pipes;
  · execution of several commands ot once;
  · black screen border (V39);
  · sprites appearance on screen border (V39);
  · alert display time (V39);
  · number of floppy disk retries (in case of an error);
  · dispatcher quantum setting.
      An information about current settings is printed.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}CLICK@{ub} - enables drive clicking;
      @{b}NOCLICK@{ub} - disables drive clicking;
      @{b}STAR@{ub} - enables use of @{i}* @{ui}as a replacement for @{i}#?@{ui};
      @{b}NOCLICK@{ub} - disables use of @{i}* @{ui}as a replacement for @{i}#?@{ui};
      @{b}PIPE@{ub}=@{i}PipeChar @{ui}- sets char to be recognized by Shell as pipe. Only one
  char is used. If you supply empty string, default char is assumed (@{i}pipe@{ui}).
      @{b}NOPIPE@{ub} - disables piping;
      @{b}MULTI@{ub}=@{i}MultiCommandChar @{ui}- sets char to be recognized by Shell as
  multiple commands char. Only one char is used. If you supply empty string,
  default char is assumed (@{i}backslash@{ui}).
      @{b}NOMULTI@{ub} - disables multiple execution;
      @{b}BORBLANK@{ub} - enables black screen border;
      @{b}NOBORBLANK@{ub} - disables black screen border;
      @{b}BORSPRITES@{ub} - allows sprites to appear on screen border;
      @{b}NOBORSPRITES@{ub} - disallows sprites to appear on screen border;
      @{b}ALERT@{ub}=@{i}AlertDisplayTime @{ui}- sets length of alert display time. The time
  is given in display frames (there are 50 frames/second in PAL,
  60 frames/second in NTSC). 0 means no alert.
      @{b}RETRY@{ub}=@{i}NumberOfRetries @{ui}- sets number of retries for floppy disk access.
  Set to zero will force any errors to be reported immediately. Set to some
  higher value will cause AmigaDOS to try to read bad track(s)
  @{i}NumberOfRetries@{ui} times. Choosing a low value is recommended if you
  use non-standard formats (CrossDOS, DiskSpare), since such disks will get
  recognized much faster.
      @{b}QUANTUM@{ub}=@{i}QuantumFrames @{ui}- sets the duration (expressed in display
  frames) for which the task is allowed to run before next task is scheduled
  for execution. This number must be in 1-50 range (default Exec's value is
  4). The lower number is, the more responsive system feels (at the cost of
  slightly worse performance).
      @{b}QUIET@{ub} - suppresses informational messages.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "ClickStart NOCLICK STAR"} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} NOCLICK STAR
        ; Disable clicking, enable @{i}* @{ui}wildcard
@{"Test" system "ClickStart ALERT 0"} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} ALERT 0
        ; Don't display alerts
@{"Test" system "ClickStart RETRY 0"} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} RETRY 0
        ; Force floppies errors to be reported immediately, speed up foreign
        ; formats recognition.
@{"Test" system "ClickStart QUANTUM 1"} @{b}ClickStart@{ub} QUANTUM 1
        ; Makes system more responsive under heavy multi-tasking.

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      There are two versions of @{b}ClickStart@{ub} included: one for AmigaDOS 2.04 or
  higher and one for AmigaDOS 3.0 higher. AmigaDOS 3.0 version (V39) is
  bigger, but has more options.
      This program does nothing illegal: it just sets some values (flags) in
  some structures. It installs no patches and uses no additional memory.
  Ideal for placement in @{i}Startup-Sequence@{ui}.
      Piping and multi-command execution are enabled by setting @{u}local@{uu} shell
  variables @{i}_pchar @{ui}and @{i}_mchar@{ui}. Therefore if you want pipes in every shell,
  you should use @{b}ClickStart@{ub} in @{i}Startup-Sequence@{ui}.
      Border options require ECS chipset.
      To fully utilize pipes and multiple commands execution you also need
  @{b}Pipe@{ub} command. It can be found on Aminet: @{i}util/cli/hacks204.lha@{ui}, but it
  seems to be a little buggy.
      Alert display times are preserved across warm-boots.
@endnode

@node Examine "Examine"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Examine@{ub} - examine type of file using @{"DataTypes" link DataTypes}

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Examine@{ub} [@{i}Dir@{ui}] [@{b}GROUPID=@{ub}@{i}Group@{ui}] [@{b}TYPEID=@{ub}@{i}Type@{ui}] [@{b}FULL@{ub}] [@{b}ID@{ub}] [@{b}ALL@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}Examine@{ub} "DIR/M,GROUPID=G/K,TYPEID=T/K,FULL/S,ID/S,ALL/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}Examine@{ub} examines types of specified files using @{"DataTypes" link DataTypes}. Name of
  the file, name of group it belongs to and descriptive class name are
  printed. ID's for group and type may be printed as well.
      By default (no files supplied) it examines current directory. You can
  use @{b}Examine@{ub} to search for specified types of files (eg. pictures or 8SVX
  sounds) by specyfying @{b}GROUPID@{ub} or @{b}TYPEID@{ub}. These should be no longer than 4
  letters and are case-sensitive. Subdirectories can be scanned using @{b}ALL@{ub}
  option. @{b}DIR@{ub} parameter can be either directory (or volume) or file pattern.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}DIR@{ub} - name of directories or files (wildcards allowed) to be examined;
      @{b}GROUPID@{ub}=@{i}Group @{ui}- print informations about files belonging
  to @{i}Group @{ui}only;
      @{b}TYPEID@{ub}=@{i}Type @{ui}- print informations about files belonging
  to @{i}Type @{ui}only;
      @{b}FULL@{ub} - print full path of examined file;
      @{b}ID@{ub} - print group ID and type ID that the file belongs to;
      @{b}ALL@{ub} - scan subdirectories as well.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "Examine ID"} @{b}Examine@{ub} @{i}ID@{ui}
        ; Examine all files in current directory, printing group ID and
        ; type ID.
@{"Test" system "Examine DH0:#? GROUPID pict ALL"} @{b}Examine@{ub} @{i}DH0:#? @{ui}GROUPID @{i}pict @{ui}ALL
        ; Find all pictures on partition DH0:
@{"Test" system "Examine DH0:#? DH1: DH2: TYPEID amig FULL ALL"} @{b}Examine@{ub} @{i}DH0:#? DH1: DH2: @{ui}TYPEID @{i}amig @{ui}FULL ALL
        ; Scan entire disk searching for AmigaGuide files.
        ; Print them with full path.
@{"Test" system "Examine S:"} @{b}Examine@{ub} @{i}S:@{ui}
        ; Examine contents of S: directory
@{"Test" system "Examine Work:Music/Modules"} @{b}Examine@{ub} @{i}Work:Music/Modules @{ui}ALL
        ; Examine type of modules you have
@endnode

@node For "For"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}For@{ub} - do command for multiple arguments

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}For@{ub} [@{b}ALL@{ub}] [@{b}DIRS@{ub}] [@{b}NOQUOTE@{ub}] [@{i}FilePattern@{ui}] [@{i}Command@{ui}] or
      @{b}For@{ub} [@{b}ALL@{ub}] [@{b}DIRS@{ub}] [@{b}NOQUOTE@{ub}] [@{i}FilePatterns@{ui}] @{b}DO@{ub} @{i}Command@{ui}

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}For@{ub} "FILE/M,DO/K/F,ALL/S,DIRS/S,NOQUOTE=NQ/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}For@{ub} runs specified command for multiple arguments. You can use current
  argument's name in command by using @{i}%S @{ui}or @{i}%P@{ui}. @{i}%S @{ui}is replaced with file's
  name, @{i}%P @{ui}is replaced with full path. File names are automatically being
  taken into quotes. If no @{b}COMMAND@{ub} is supplied, then simple execution is
  assumed (@{i}%S @{ui}pattern).
      In case you specify more than one file pattern, @{b}DO@{ub} keyword must appear
  before command. If you specify no file pattern, @{b}FOR@{ub} assumes @{i}#? @{ui}(all files
  in current directory).

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}FILE@{ub} - file(s) to execute command for;
      @{b}DO@{ub} - command line to execute for a file;
      @{b}ALL@{ub} - scan subdirectories as well;
      @{b}DIRS@{ub} - call command for directory names too;
      @{b}NOQUOTE@{ub} - prevent files from being taken into quotes.
      Please note that switches (@{b}ALL@{ub}, @{b}DIRS@{ub} and @{b}NOQUOTE@{ub}) must appear @{u}before@{uu}
  command text.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "For RAM:#?"} @{b}For@{ub} @{i}RAM:#?@{ui}
        ; Run all files on Ram Disk
@{"Test" system "For DEVS:Monitors/~(#?.info) %S"} @{b}For@{ub} @{i}DEVS:Monitors/~(#?.info) @{ui}@{i}%S@{ui}
        ; Run all monitor drivers - replaces two instructions from
        ; original Startup-Sequence.
        ; Note that full path is not necessary - current directory is
        ; changed automagically for each argument.
@{"Test" system "For ALL SYS:#? Work:#? NQ DO Echo '%s'"} @{b}For@{ub} ALL @{i}SYS:#? @{ui}@{i}Work:#? @{ui}NQ DO @{i}Echo '%s'@{ui}
        ; List emulation
@{"Test" system "For ALL C:#? Version %s"} @{b}For@{ub} ALL @{i}C:#? @{ui}@{i}Version %s@{ui}
        ; Get versions of all DOS commands
@endnode

@node RXControl "RXControl"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}RXControl@{ub} - control ARexx

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}RXControl@{ub} [@{b}CANCEL@{ub}] [@{b}HALT@{ub}] [@{b}SUSPEND@{ub}|@{b}RESUME@{ub}] [@{b}TRACESTART@{ub}|@{b}TRACEEND@{ub}]
                [@{b}CONOPEN@{ub}|@{b}CONCLOSE@{ub}] [@{b}QUIET@{ub}]

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}RXControl@{ub} "RXC=CANCEL/S,HI=HALT/S,SUSPEND/S,RESUME/S,TS=TRACESTART/S,
                 TE=TRACEEND/S,TCO=CONOPEN/S,TCC=CONCLOSE/S,QUIET/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}RXControl@{ub} controls internals of ARexx interpreter. It may be run
  only after @{i}RexxMast@{ui}. 

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}CANCEL@{ub} - stop ARexx server. It will be stopped after all ARexx
  programs finish their execution (equivalent to @{i}RXC @{ui}command);
      @{b}HALT@{ub} - immediately stop all executing ARexx programs (equivalent to @{i}HI@{ui}
  command);
      @{b}SUSPEND@{ub} - suspend execution of all ARexx programs;
      @{b}RESUME@{ub} - resume execution of all ARexx programs (suspended with
  @{b}SUSPEND@{ub} option);
      @{b}TRACESTART@{ub} - sets global tracing mode for all ARexx programs
  (equivalent to @{i}TS @{ui}command);
      @{b}TRACEEND@{ub} - disables global tracing mode enabled with @{b}TRACESTART@{ub} option
  (equivalent to @{i}TE @{ui}command);
      @{b}CONOPEN@{ub} - opens special console for tracing ARexx programs (equivalent
  to @{i}TCO @{ui}command);
      @{b}CONCLOSE@{ub} - closes tracing console opened with @{b}CONOPEN@{ub} option
  (equivalent to @{i}TCC @{ui}command);
      @{b}QUIET@{ub} - suppresses informational messages.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "RXControl HALT CANCEl"} @{b}RXControl@{ub} @{i}HALT @{ui}@{i}CANCEL@{ui}
        ; Stop all ARexx programs and stop ARexx server
@{"Test" system "RXControl CONOPEN TRACESTART"} @{b}RXControl@{ub} @{i}CONOPEN @{ui}@{i}TRACESTART@{ui}
        ; Open tracing console and start tracing ARexx programs

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      The main purpose of this @{b}RXControl@{ub} is to provide complete control of
  ARexx in one command. This command is a replacement for most of ARexx
  control commands from @{i}SYS:Rexxc @{ui}directory (@{"Show aliases" link
  S/RX-Startup/main}).
      For full compatibility, this command may be run from Workbench (you
  must make an icon yourself). It accepts all switches described above as
  ToolTypes. If you don't use @{b}QUIET@{ub}, it will display a requester describing
  current state of ARexx.
@endnode

@node Time "Time"

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Time@{ub} - time command execution

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Time@{ub} [@{b}NOHEADER@{ub}] @{i}Command @{ui}

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}Time@{ub} "NOHEAD/S,COMMAND/F/A"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}Time@{ub} executes specified command and measures time it takes to complete
  it. This time is then printed in seconds and microseconds.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}NOHEAD@{ub} - only time (without any additional messages) is printed
  (useful in scripts);
      @{b}COMMAND@{ub} - command to time (with parameters);
      Please note that @{b}NOHEAD@{ub} switch must appear @{u}before@{uu} command text.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "Time Copy C:#? RAM:"} @{b}Time@{ub} @{i}Copy C:#? RAM:@{ui}
        ; Find out how long it takes to copy C: directory commands to
        ; Ram Disk
@{"Test" system "Time NOHEAD List LIBS:#? ALL"} @{b}Time@{ub} NOHEAD @{i}List LIBS:#? ALL@{ui}
        ; Print execution time of List command

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      If you redirect output of command being @{b}Time@{ub}d to another stream, the
  results of @{b}Time@{ub} will also go there. To avoid such situation, redirect
  output of @{b}Time@{ub} too, as in following example:
@{"Test" system "Time >CONSOLE: NOHEAD List >NIL: ENV:#?.info ALL"} @{b}Time@{ub} >CONSOLE: NOHEAD @{i}List >NIL: ENV:#?.info ALL@{ui}
@endnode

@node Touch "Touch"
@next Touch

@{fg highlight}NAME@{fg text}
      @{b}Touch@{ub} - change date of last modification for files

@{fg highlight}SYNOPSIS@{fg text}
      @{b}Touch@{ub} [@{i}Files@{ui}] [@{b}ONEDATE@{ub}] [@{b}ALL@{ub}] [@{b}QUIET@{ub}] 

@{fg highlight}TEMPLATE@{fg text}
      @{b}Touch@{ub} "FILE/M,ONEDATE/S,ALL/S,QUIET/S"

@{fg highlight}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}
      @{b}Touch@{ub} changes date and time of last file modification to current
  system date for specified files. With @{b}ALL@{ub} option subdirectories will be
  affected as well. Normally, current date is used for each file (therefore
  files @{b}Touch@{ub}'ed with one command can have different dates). @{b}ONEDATE@{ub} forces
  same date and time for all files. This version differs from the Unix one in
  that it doesn't create empty files or directories.

@{fg highlight}PARAMETERS@{fg text}
      @{b}FILE@{ub} - file(s) to touch;
      @{b}ONEDATE@{ub} - use one date for all files;
      @{b}ALL@{ub} - scan subdirectories as well;
      @{b}QUIET@{ub} - don't print any messages.

@{fg highlight}EXAMPLES@{fg text}
@{"Test" system "Touch"} @{b}Touch@{ub}
        ; Touch all files in current directory
@{"Test" system "Touch #?.o #?.gst #?.c"} @{b}Touch@{ub} @{i}#?.o @{ui}@{i}#?.gst @{ui}@{i}#?.c @{ui}
        ; Prepare files for Make

@{fg highlight}NOTES@{fg text}
      Directories will be @{b}Touch@{ub}ed too, right after files.
@endnode

@node DataTypes "DataTypes Information"
@prev DataTypes
@next DataTypes

  @{b}@{u}DataTypes@{uu}@{ub}

      @{i}DataTypes @{ui}is an AmigaDOS subsystem (introduced in AmigaDOS 3.0) for
  dealing with different types of files found on different machines (PC's,
  Macs and Amigas). @{i}DataTypes @{ui}can be used for recognizing types of files
  and interpreting informations in this files. An example of the latter is
  @{i}MultiView@{ui}, which can show many types of data.

      For @{i}DataTypes  @{ui}to work the following files are needed:
      · LIBS:datatypes.library;
      · DEVS:DataTypes/#? - these short files contain information necessary
        to determine type of file;
      · LIBS:DataTypes/#? - these shared libraries are used for interpreting
        contents of the file.
      Because @{"Examine" link Examine} command tests files, it needs DEVS:DataTypes/#?
  @{u}only@{uu}. Unfortunately, these descriptions are not easy to create or edit,
  as there is no program that does it (although I've heard that licensed
  developers have something...). Currently I'm writing one, but it may take
  some time until it's finished (if you desperately need it, send me some
  money, so I can work faster :-).

      @{i}DataTypes @{ui}divide all files into the following main categories:
      · @{i}syst @{ui}(System) - system files;
      · @{i}text @{ui}(Text) - textual files;
      · @{i}docu @{ui}(Document) - documents (spreadsheet data, text with
        pictures etc.);
      · @{i}soun @{ui}(Sound) - sound samples;
      · @{i}inst @{ui}(Instrument) - musical instruments;
      · @{i}musi @{ui}(Music) - songs;
      · @{i}pict @{ui}(Picture) - graphics;
      · @{i}anim @{ui}(Animation) - animations;
      · @{i}movi @{ui}(Movie) - animation with sound.
      The categories are identified by four letter (case sensitive) group
  ID's (first column of above table). Each category is further divided into
  types: for example a @{i}picture @{ui}could be: @{i}gif@{ui}, @{i}ilbm @{ui}or @{i}pcx @{ui}and @{i}text @{ui}could
  be @{i}asci @{ui}or @{i}FTXT@{ui}. Again, each type is identified by up to 4 letters and
  type names are case-sensitive. These unique identifiers are used by
  @{"Examine" link Examine 15} command as @{b}GROUPID@{ub} and @{b}TYPEID@{ub} and are printed if you use @{b}ID@{ub}
  option.
@endnode

